1. Baseline Parameters
The core configuration applied across all experiments unless otherwise specified:

a. Target Image Size: Dynamically initialized to a minimum of 224 x 224 based on the dataset's median dimensions.
b. Data Split: 80% Training / 20% Validation, stratified by class labels to maintain distribution.
c. Test Transformations: Standardized resizing and center cropping. No artificial augmentation applied to test data.
d. Training Duration: 20 Epochs.

2. Experiment 1: Baseline Architecture
![alt text](image.png)

Methodology: 
    The baseline model utilizes a custom 3-block Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) architecture. 
    Each block consists of a Conv2D layer (32, 64, and 128 filters respectively) paired with MaxPooling2D for downsampling. 
    The network concludes with a flattened dense layer of 128 nodes, a 50% dropout rate for basic regularization, 
    and a 3-node softmax output. Basic resizing and cropping were applied to the training data.

Results:
    Final Test Loss: 0.5546
    Final Test Accuracy: 0.9273

Analysis:
    Overall Performance: The baseline model performs adequately on raw data, achieving a validation accuracy of over 90%.
    Mid-Training Instability: Training exhibits volatility, notably around epochs 11–12, where training loss spikes and accuracy temporarily drops.
    Signs of Overfitting: By epochs 18–20, training accuracy reaches 1.0 while validation accuracy plateaus. 
                            The divergence between the decreasing training loss and the plateauing validation loss 
                            indicates the model is beginning to memorize the training data rather than generalizing.

3. Experiment 2: Data Augmentation
![alt text](image-1.png)

Methodology:
    To combat the overfitting observed in the baseline, dynamic image augmentation was introduced 
    to the training dataset. The model architecture remains identical to the baseline.

Key Code Modification:
train_transforms = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize(256),
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
    transforms.RandomRotation(degrees=60),
    transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2),
    transforms.CenterCrop((target_height, target_width)),
    transforms.ToTensor()
])

Results:
    Final Test Loss : 0.2621
    Final Test Accuracy : 0.9455

Analysis:
    Improved Generalization: Unlike the baseline, training and validation accuracy track each other 
                                closely throughout the 20 epochs, both finishing above 95%.
    Resolved Overfitting: Training loss no longer significantly undercuts validation loss. 
                            The tight convergence at the end of the run confirms the model is learning 
                            generalizable features rather than memorizing exact pixel layouts.
    Expected Volatility: The validation loss exhibits expected short-term volatility (e.g., epoch 12). 
                            Because the model evaluates newly mutated variations of the images every epoch, 
                            the learning curve is noisier, but the resulting classifier is significantly more robust.

Conclusion: The application of image augmentation directly improved the model's ability to generalize to unseen data, 
            successfully resolving the late-stage overfitting seen in the baseline.

4. Experiment 3: Transfer Learning
![alt text](image-2.png)

Methodology:
    This experiment discards the custom CNN architecture in favor of a pre-trained MobileNetV2 model. 
    The base model weights (trained on ImageNet) were frozen, acting as an optimized feature extractor. 
    Only a new, custom dense classification head was trained. The data augmentation strategy from Experiment 2 was retained.

Key Code Modification:
keras.config.set_image_data_format('channels_first')
base_model = keras.applications.MobileNetV2(
    input_shape=(3, 224, 224), 
    include_top=False, 
    weights='imagenet'
)

base_model.trainable = False

model = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Input(shape=(3, 224, 224)),
    
    # Preprocessing: MobileNetV2 expects pixel values between [-1, 1].
    # Your PyTorch ToTensor() outputs [0, 1], so we scale it here automatically.
    keras.layers.Rescaling(scale=2.0, offset=-1.0),
    
    # Pass the scaled images through the frozen MobileNetV2 base
    base_model,
    
    # Compress the spatial dimensions while retaining feature depth.
    # Crucial: specify channels_first to maintain PyTorch backend compatibility.
    keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(data_format="channels_first"),
    
    # Add your custom dense layers for the 3 fruit classes
    keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
    keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax')
])

Results:
    Final Test Loss: 0.0031
    Final Test Accuracy: 1.0000

Analysis:
    Immediate Convergence: Validation accuracy starts at approximately 1.0 on Epoch 1 and remains flat, 
                            with training accuracy aligning by Epoch 2. The model did not require time 
                            to learn fundamental visual features like edges or shapes.
    Feature Extraction Efficacy: Because MobileNetV2 already possessed highly optimized feature maps for 
                                    identifying natural objects, it took precisely one pass over the data 
                                    to map these pre-learned features to the specific fruit classes.
    Absence of Overfitting: Both training and validation loss drop to near-zero and remain tightly coupled. 
                            The frozen base model successfully prevented network memorization.

Final Conclusion:
    The transfer learning approach drastically outperformed the custom-built CNN. 
    While the custom model (even with augmentation) required 15–20 epochs to stabilize at ~95% accuracy, 
    the pre-trained MobileNetV2 architecture achieved near-perfect accuracy and stabilization by Epoch 2. 
    This proves the extreme efficiency and operational superiority of leveraging pre-trained feature 
    extractors for standard image classification tasks.

